<section>
  <title><xref ref="S_quantifier"></xref></title>
  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_sec24-1"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      <li>
        <title>(a)</title>
        <p>
          There exists a rational number <m>x</m> such that <m>x^2 - 3x - 7 = 0</m>.
          This statement is false since the solutions of the equation are <m>x = \dfrac{3 \pm \sqrt{37}}{2}</m>,
          which are irrational numbers.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>(b)</title>
        <p>
          There exists a real number <m>x</m> such that <m>x^2 + 1 = 0</m>.
          This statement is false since the only solutions of the equation are <m>i</m> and <m>-i</m>,
          which are not real numbers.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>(c)</title>
        <p>
          There exists a natural number <m>m</m> such that <m>m^2 \lt 1</m>.
          This statement is false because if <m>m</m> is a natural number,
          then <m>m \geq 1</m> and hence, <m>m^2 \geq 1</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_sec24-2new"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      <li>
        <title>(a)</title>
        <p>
          <m>m = 1</m> is a counterexample.
          The negation is: There exists a natural number <m>m</m> such that <m>m^2</m> is not even or there exists a natural number <m>m</m> such that <m>m^2</m> is odd.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>(b)</title>
        <p>
          <m>x = 0</m> is a counterexample.
          The negation is: There exists a real number <m>x</m> such that <m>x^2 \leq 0</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>(f)</title>
        <p>
          <m>x = \dfrac{\pi}{2}</m> is a counterexample.
          The negation is: There exists a real number <m>x</m> such that <m>\tan^2 x + 1 \ne \sec^2 x</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_sec24-2"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(a)}}
      \item There exists a rational number <m>x</m> such that <m>x > \sqrt{2}</m>.
      The negation is <m>\left( {\forall x \in \mathbb{Q}} \right)\left( {x \leq \sqrt 2 } \right)</m>, which is, For each rational number <m>x</m>, <m>x \le \sqrt{2}</m>.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(c)}}
      \item For each integer <m>x</m>, <m>x</m> is even or <m>x</m> is odd.
      The negation is <m>\left( \exists x \in \mathbb{Z} \right) \left( x \text{ is odd and \(x\) is even }  \right)</m>, which is, There exists an integer <m>x</m> such that <m>x</m> is odd and <m>x</m> is even.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(e)}}
      \item For each integer <m>x</m>, if <m>x^2</m> is odd, then <m>x</m> is odd.
      The negation is <m>\left( \exists x \in \mathbb{Z} \right) \left( x^2 \text{ is odd and \(x\) is even }  \right)</m>, which is, There exists an integer <m>x</m> such that <m>x^2</m> is odd and <m>x</m> is even.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(h)}}
      \item There exists a real number <m>x</m> such that <m>\cos \left( 2x \right) = 2 \left( \cos x \right)</m>.
      The negation is <m>\left( {\forall x \in \mathbb{R}} \right) \left( \cos \left( 2x \right) \ne 2 \left( \cos x \right) \right)</m>, which is, For each real number <m>x</m>, <m>\cos \left( 2x \right) \ne 2 \left( \cos x \right)</m>.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_sec24-3"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(a)}}
      \item There exist integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> such that <m>m > n</m>.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(e)}}
      \item There exists an integer <m>n</m> such that for each integer <m>m</m>, <m>m^2 > n</m>.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_sec24-4"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(a)}}
      \item <m>\left( \forall m \right) \left( \forall n \right) \left( m \le n \right)</m>.
      For all integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>, <m>m \le n</m>.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(e)}}
      \item <m>\left( \forall n \right) \left( \exists m \right) \left( m^2 \le n \right)</m>.
      For each integer <m>n</m>, there exists an integer <m>m</m> such that  <m>m^2 \le n</m>.
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="Exer_quantifier1"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      <li>
        <title>(a)</title>
        <p>
          It is not a statement since <m>x</m> is an unquantified variable.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>(d)</title>
        <p>
          It is a true statement.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>(c)</title>
        <p>
          It is a false statement.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>(d)</title>
        <p>
          It is a true statement.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title>(e)</title>
        <p>
          <m>\left\{ -20, -10, -5, -4, -2, -1, 1, 2, 4, 5, 10, 20 \right\}</m>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </ul>
  <ul>
    {{ <xref ref="exer_24-increasing"></xref>.}}
    \item
    <ul>
      {{(a)}}
      \item A function <m>f</m> with domain <m>\R</m> is strictly increasing provided that
      <m>\left( \forall x, y \in \R \right) \left[ \left( x \lt  y \right) \to \left( f(x) \lt  f(y) \right) \right]</m>.
    </ul>
  </ul>
</section>